clinical_study.official_title: Phase II Efficacy of Cranberry Powder in Preventing Catheter-associated Urinary Tract Infection Post Elective Gynecological Surgery

collaborator.agency: National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases (NIDDK)

brief_summary.textblock: Approximately 10-27% of patients undergoing gynecologic surgeries develop a catheter associated urinary tract infection (CAUTI) in the post operatory period, as bladder catheterization is a common practice in gynecologic surgery. Cranberry products provide alternative means for preventing CAUTI and could result in decreased use of antimicrobials. In this pilot study we will enroll 200 women post gynecologic surgery and randomize them to take either cranberry powder capsules or placebo powder capsules. The low risk of harm associated with using cranberry to reduce UTI coupled with its potential benefit makes it a desirable intervention for the prevention of CAUTI. The conduct/ results of this pilot /feasibility study will prepare us for the conduct of a large scale clinical trial.

detailed_description.textblock: Cranberry products prevent bacteria that cause UTI, especially Escherichia coli, from adhering to bladder cell wall thus preventing infection. Adherence of type 1 pili is inhibited by the fructose and of p pili by the proanthocyanidins present in cranberry.

study_design_info.masking: Quadruple (Participant, Care Provider, Investigator, Outcomes Assessor)

primary_outcome.measure: Participants With Clinically-diagnosed and Treated UTI's.
primary_outcome.time_frame: From surgery to post-op visit, approximately 6 weeks post surgery
primary_outcome.description: The primary endpoint was the number of participants who were clinically-diagnosed and treated for UTI whether or not results from a urine culture were available. All UTI's were confirmed via medical records.

arm_group.description: TheraCranÂ® cranberry: based upon proanthocyanidin content, the four cranberry capsules are equivalent to two 8-ounce servings of cranberry juice. Participants were directed to take two capsules by mouth twice each day (once in the morning and once in the evening) starting at time of discharge for 4-6 weeks, or until their return for their post-operative doctor's visit. Participants were instructed to drink an 8 oz glass of water while taking the capsule with or without food.

Placebo: participants were directed to take two capsules by mouth twice each day (once in the morning and once in the evening) starting at time of discharge for 4-6 weeks, or until their return for their post-operative doctor's visit. Participants were instructed to drink an 8 oz glass of water while taking the capsule with or without food.

intervention.description: 2 cranberry powder capsules twice a day

criteria.textblock:
Inclusion Criteria:
1. Presenting at the gynecology clinic for a pre-operatory visit
2. Ability to give informed consent
3. Willing to take cranberry capsules for up to 6 weeks
4. 18 of age or older
Exclusion Criteria:
1. Pregnancy
2. History of nephrolithiasis
3. History of allergy to cranberry
4. Patient on anticoagulant medicine to be re-started during the 4-6 weeks after surgery
5. Less than 18 years old

results_reference.citation: Foxman B, Cronenwett AE, Spino C, Berger MB, Morgan DM. Cranberry juice capsules and urinary tract infection after surgery: results of a randomized trial. Am J Obstet Gynecol. 2015 Aug;213(2):194.e1-8. doi: 10.1016/j.ajog.2015.04.003. Epub 2015 Apr 13.

responsible_party.investigator_title: Hunein F & Hilda Maassab Professor of Epidemiology

participant_flow.recruitment_details: Participants were recruited at their preoperative appointment for gynecological surgery. At enrollment they completed a questionnaire about their history and signed an informed consent form. Participants were not assigned to a treatment arm until the day of their surgery.
participant_flow.pre_assignment_details: If a participant's surgery was canceled or she failed to complete her enrollment questionnaire she was not assigned to a treatment arm. 200 women were consented, 160 were randomly assigned to treatment (80 cranberry, 80 placebo).

reported_events.time_frame: Adverse Events data were collected beginning at time of randomization (admitted to surgery) and ended 30 days after their postoperative visit when study treatment ended (a total time period of 8-10 weeks).
reported_events.desc: Adverse Events (AE) data were gathered via scheduled followup phone calls with participants and medical record review. UTI was an outcome and so was not reported as AE unless other pertinent symptoms occurred. Some severe AE's reported occurred before randomization but are reported here due to their severe nature.

event.sub_title: Altered mental status and progressive fatigue due to chronic anemia
event.description: Participant told pups that she started feeling disoriented, tired and could not talk in the morning. She went to the hospital and was admitted for two days. She underwent a blood transfusion and received two pints of blood.
The participant was admitted to the chest pain center in stable condition.
hip repair previous to gynecological surgery and study drug.

Participant said she had back pain and found out it was a fracture. She had a vertebroplasty compression. Participant said that the back pain went away 2 days after the procedure. She was given oxycontin and Flexeril

While watching television she had a sudden headache `all over` along with a sore feeling in both her eyes, as well as one bout of emesis. Headaches continued in the morning so she went to emergency dept. She does not have any other meningeal signs.
Surgery was not performed and PARTICIPANT NEVER RECEIVED STUDY DRUG

event.sub_title: Pulmonary Embolus in Right Lower Lobe
event.description: Participant did not recover well from operation for incarcerated hernia so she has a CT scan that showed acute pulmonary embolus in the right lower lobe pulmonary artery branches.

event.sub_title: Transfusion related acute lung injury versus post operative pneumonia
event.description: PARTICIPANT DID NOT TAKE STUDY DRUG. Participant was kept in the hospital after gynecologic because of transfusion related acute lung injury.
